//
// Prod-5a: sealed ledger fixture.
//
// Compact's `sealed ledger NAME: T;` declares a ledger field that is
// writable from the constructor (or `pure` setup circuits) but NOT
// writable from non-pure circuits — sealed fields are effectively
// "compile-time write-protected" after init. At the StateValue /
// AlignedValue level they serialize identically to a regular ledger
// field; the frontend enforces the no-write rule via type checking.
//
// This fixture exercises:
//   - a sealed ledger field of `Field` (admin: initialized to a literal
//     value in the constructor — the natural use case for an immutable
//     contract-owner address),
//   - a sealed ledger field of `Bytes<32>` (contract_id: initialized
//     from `pad(32, "lares:sealed:demo")` in the constructor —
//     exercises Prod-15's Bytes<L>-from-pad byte-parity confirmation),
//   - a sealed ledger field of `Uint<64>` (created_at: initialized to
//     a literal in the constructor — exercises Prod-13's tunsigned
//     literal coercion alongside Prod-9's tfield branch),
//   - a regular ledger field of `Boolean` (flag, writable by ping()),
// to lock in byte-parity for sealed declarations.
//
// The Field-typed sealed field doubles as a regression test for Prod-9:
// integer literals at a Field-typed RHS must be wrapped in `Fr::from(N)`
// at the Rust emitter so the downstream ledger-write builder's
// `Into<AlignedValue>` bound is satisfied. Before that fix, the
// `admin = 42` line emitted `let tmp = 42;` (i32) and failed to compile.
//
// The Uint<64>-typed sealed field locks in Prod-13: a literal RHS at
// `Uint<N>` type must be emitted with the matching `u<N>` suffix so the
// builder's `Into<AlignedValue>` bound matches the field's primitive
// (`let tmp = 100u64;` rather than `let tmp = 100;`).
//
// The Bytes<32>-typed sealed field locks in Prod-15: a prior diagnostic
// had hypothesised an on-wire encoding divergence between Rust and TS
// for `pad(L, "...")` (Compress atom vs fixed-width bytes). In fact the
// per-cell encoding is byte-identical — both sides serialise a fixed-
// width `AlignmentAtom::Bytes { length: L }` atom whose payload is the
// UTF-8 string bytes followed by zero-padding. The apparent size
// discrepancy in the earlier report came from unrelated container-level
// structure (operations map / pure-circuit emission), not from the
// Bytes<L> cell itself. This fixture pins that result.
//
// Three writes in one constructor body also exercise Prod-14: the
// frontend lowers each `ledger = expr` into a fresh `const tmp = …;
// ledger = tmp;` pair. Before Prod-14, the emitter generated multiple
// `let tmp = ...` lines that shadowed each other, so every cell read
// the value of the last binding. With Prod-14, the second/third
// bindings rename to `tmp_0`, `tmp_1`, …, preserving each write.

import CompactStandardLibrary;

export sealed ledger admin: Field;
export sealed ledger contract_id: Bytes<32>;
export sealed ledger created_at: Uint<64>;
export ledger flag: Boolean;

constructor() {
  admin = 42;
  contract_id = pad(32, "lares:sealed:demo");
  created_at = 12345;
}

export circuit ping(): [] {
  flag.write(true);
}
